This document acts as a novice tutorial behind explaining what several JSON properties do, specifically for Itemtypes.

    code: "xxx"
    Code determines what other files or code will need to refer the item as. You do not need to add a domain ("game:" or "modname:") before it, but will need to do so elsewhere. For example, if you write `code: "apple"`, other JSONS or code refer to this specific JSON as `modname:apple`.

    variantgroups: [      ]
    Variantgroups makes the game recognize there's more subtypes of this item than just the default you will describe below. Moving onwards, you can add "ByType" behind a property that will make that specific property only apply to those specific variants. ByType is a crazy powerful asset to make your items (and blocks) unique, and saves you work from making standalone JSONS that share a lot of other properties otherwise. Variantgroups's array can be filled in with the following subproperties:

        code: "xxx"
        Unlike to before, in this array Code will determine what THIS Json needs to refer the variant as through wildcard. For example, if you write `code: "metal"`, any further JSON code that uses {metal} in its values/arguments will automatically replace this wildcard with any and all possible states as you decide below.

        loadFromProperties: "xxx"
        If your list of available states already exists in a third party JSON listing the items, you can immediately pull this from a properties folder file using this subproperty. You can use an existing vanilla properties list like `game:ore`, or your own list like `modname:gemstones`

        states: [ "xxx", "yyy", cont...]
        States describe which valid variants exist for the afore mentioned codename. If you mentioned Metal as example, here is where you can fill in Copper, Tin, Iron, etc.

    You can repeat these grouped subproprties any amount of times if your item has multiple variant categories, so long they use a different codename each. Eventually, a variantsgroup code will look like so; `variantgroups: [ {code: "metal", states: ["copper", "tin"] }, {code: "gem", states: "emerald", "diamond"} ]`

    shape: { base: "xxx" }
    This code determines what shape the item or block appears as. This property needs a folder file path, and always starts directly from the 'Shapes' folder. As example from above, and which keeps applying to below; if an item differs shapes based on its variants (and going -ByType isn't necessary), you can write `shape: { base: misc/flag{size} }` if you have set different variants for flag sizes this item. Assuming 'small' and 'large' are two stated variants, this will automaticaly give the two unique items the shapes from file `modname/shapes/misc/flagsmall.json` and `modname/shapes/misc/flaglarge.json`.

